<a name = "power-series"><b> Power Series </b></a>
<p>
	<ul>
		<li>
			The power series is of the form
			\[
				\sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n (z - z_0)^n,
			\]
			and the radius of convergence is always a disc (by the ratio test)
			<ul>
				<li>
					The series converges if and only if 
					$\lim_{n\to \infty} \left|\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n}\right| |z-z_0| < 1.$
				</li>
			</ul>
		</li>

		<li>
			Note also that for a power series, a convergence implies 
			a uniform convergence (so we can swap sum and integral, or
			sum and derivative).
		</li>

		<li>
			Def: A function $f(z)$ is <em>holomorphic</em> at $z = z_0$
			if it is differentiable at $z = z_0$ and 
			in a small neighborhood of that point.
		</li>
		<li>
			Def: A function $f(z)$ is <em>analytic</em> at $z = z_0$
			if it can be represented by a power series
			$f(z) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n(z - z_0)^n$
			and that series converge for some open disc centered at
			$z = z_0.$
		</li>
		<li>
			<b>BIG IDEA:</b> Analytic $\Leftrightarrow$ Holomorphic.
			<ul>
				<li> Proof idea: Take the derivative of the power series, and use the 
					uniform convergence to swap the sum and 
					the derivative.
				</li>
				<li>
					Note that 
					\[
						a_n = \frac{1}{2\pi i}\oint \frac{f(\zeta)}{(\zeta - z_0)^{n+1}}d\zeta
						= \frac{f^{(n)}(z_0)}{n!},
					\]
					which agrees with the Taylor series expansion.
				</li>
			</ul>
		</li>
		<li> <b>Liouville's Theorem:</b> Every bounded entire function is constant.
			<ul>
				<li> Proof idea: Use the ML bound for the power series expansion
					of the function.
				</li>
			</ul>
		</li>
	</ul>
</p>

