<a name = "singularities"><b> Singularities </b></a>
<p>
	<ul>
		<li>
			Def: A function has an <em>isolated singularity</em>
			at a point, if it it holomorphic in some
			punctured disc around that point.
		</li>
		<li>
			If $f(z)$ has an isolated singularity at $z = z_0,$
			then
			\[
				f(z) = \sum_{n=-\infty}^\infty a_n(z - z_0)^n
			\]
			and this series converges in some punctured disc
			about $z = z_0,$
			and $a_n = \frac{1}{2\pi i}\oint_C \frac{f(z)}{(z-z_0)^{n+1}}dz$
			where $C$ is a simple, closed, positively-oriented curve
			in the disc surrounding $z = z_0.$
		</li>
		<li> There are exactly three types of singularities:
			<table border="1">
				<tr>
					<td>Removable singularity</td>
					<td> $\lim_{z\to z_0} f(z)$ exists </td>
					<td> Laurent series expansion for $f$ about $z = z_0$
						has no terms with negative exponents (Taylor series)</td>
					<td> Example: $f(z) = \frac{\sin z}{z}$ around $z = 0$.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Pole</td>
					<td> $\lim_{z\to z_0} f(z)$ does NOT exists, but
					 	 $\lim_{z\to z_0} |f(z)| = +\infty$ </td>
					<td> Laurent series expansion for $f$ about $z = z_0$
						 has a finite number of terms with negative exponents</td>
					<td> Example: $f(z) = \frac{1}{z}$ around $z = 0$.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Essential Singularity</td>
					<td> neither limit exists </td>
					<td> Laurent series expansion for $f$ about $z = z_0$
						 has an infinite number of terms with negative exponents</td>
					<td> Example: $f(z) = e^{1/z}$ around $z = 0$.</td>
				</tr>
				</table>
		</li>
	</ul>
</p>